sourceOfFunds.purpose: The Trust raised funds from two sources in the FY 2015 -16. First source was the small amount donations received from various individuals. Just like the FY 2015-16, the Trust raised funds from two sources in the FY 2016 -17 also. First source was the small amount donations received from various individuals. The second source of funds was the small income received from the Government for running Training Centers under National Digital Literacy Mission - a scheme of the Ministry of Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology, Government of India.

The trust implemented the PMKVY - Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojna under the Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship, and the income thus received from the NSDC was the primary source of Income for the Trust.

The trust intends to further implement the PMKVY - Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojna under the Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship, and banks upon the income thus to be received from the NSDC, apart from the small amounts of donations.

ngoList.detailsOfAchievement: valid Characters Bringing out Resource Directories on child marriage, domestic violence and trafficking in persons has been a major achievement of Women Power Connect. We worked in collaboration with our members to get authenticated information to publish in the Directories. Successful partnerships with the corporate sector has helped Women Power Connect change the mindset in workplaces towards women employees.

sourceOfFunds.purpose: On the day of International Womens Day that is 8th March Women Power Connect with support from Care India organised a celebration on the theme of Make it Happen Respect and Dignity for all to Foster a Happy Workplace in Gurgaon. The event contained theater performance, live music and a magic show. A 100 corporates were engaged with as part of this celebration of womens day.

WomenPowerConnect (WPC) in cooperation with Afghanistan based organization called Equality for Peace and Democracy (EPD) organised a Training of Trainers programme for representatives of the Government of Afghanistan. As part of the delegation there were also representatives of the various civil societies from Afghanistan. This Training of Trainers (ToT) was held from 25th to 28th October, 2014 in New Delhi and focused on gender budgeting.

Women Power Connect worked on a project for developing the capacity of women farmers in India with support from Oxfam. As part of this project training workshops were held with women farmers across India to on issues of gender rights and legal empowerment. As part of this project tool kits were developed to help women farmers know their rights and the laws relating to property and violence against women.

Women Power Connect worked with the Ford Foundation on a project aimed at addressing child marriages in the states of Bihar, Madhya Pradesh and Jharkhand. As part of this project national and state level initiatives were undertaken to sensitize policy makers on the issue of child marriage. Women Power Connect worked with grass root level organisations in order to stop child marriages from taking place in the three States.

In this project, WomenPowerConnect as one of the implementing partners focused on drafting a Resource Directory with information about the law and stakeholder under the domestic violence Act. In addition corporates were approached and trainings were held for corporates to sensitise them on the issue of both domestic violence and sexual harassment at the workplace.
National Mission for Empowerment of Women, Women Power Connect conducted a research study evaluating schemes in Tamil Nadu

Women Power Connect held training workshops for women farmers in the states of Odisha and Uttar Pradesh as part of this project during the year 2015. Women Power Connect formed an alliance with another NGO, Mahila Kisan Adhikar Manch, and developed a Declaration for women farmers

Women Power Connect conducted gender trainings and legal empowerment trainings for women farmers in India as part of this project. We developed handbooks on laws relating to the right to property and land rights. Information about the rights women farmers have to property and land was shared at the training workshops.

In March, WPC and CARE India came together to execute an event to mark International Womens Day around the theme of Violence against Women at home and at the work place. It aimed at commemorating the struggles of women worldwide along with sending the message of gender equality, women empowerment and women as inspiring change agents.

Women Power Connect continued with its work of holding trainings for the corporate sector on the issue of domestic violence and sexual harassment at the workplace. Corporates targeted included Elin Electronics and Moser Baer. Work on developing a comprehensive Resource Diectory included holding a conference with experts on the issue of domestic violence.

Women Power Connect was involved in a project on addressing domestic violence in Delhi with support from the Population Services International. In 2016, as part of this project, we released a Resource Directory with important numbers of stakeholders under the Domestic Violence Act in Delhi. The Directory was released at a national conference organised on the issue of domestic violence and convergence in Delhi.
Women Power Connect continued its study on analysing the impact of government schemes.

Women Power Connect organised genderlogues, that is, dialogues on gender in colleges in Delhi with suppport from the Fridrich Ebert Stiftung. The genderlogues were held on the issue of women and work, women home based workers and domestic violence in the natal family. The genderlogues were held in Jamia Milia Islamia, Lady Irwin College and Bharati College.

Women Power Connect prepared two Resource Directories on Trafficking in Women and Children with support from the Asia Foundation. The Resource Directories provide information on the law, and information about important helplines and services in existence to prevent and protect survivors of traffic king. In 2016, the States of Delhi, Uttar Pradesh, and Haryana were covered as part of this study.

ngoList.detailsOfAchievement: WAG Chelsea is a Delhi based NGO and CHELSEA is an acronym for the activities that the organization is involved with in Delhi and Uttar Pradesh. The organization was founded in 1992 by a group of exArmy officers wives with the aim of preventing the spread of HIV and ensuring the dignity of those living with HIV. WAG Chelseaâ€™s vision is to provide quality health and educational services to the marginalized sections of society. The organization reaches out to MARP, providing information, links to services and advocates reduction of stigma and discriminatory practice. Over the years, WAG Chelsea has reached out to maximum people includes children through community outreach, awareness events and basic support services to OVC. The community clusters where WAG Chelsea works includes the urban slums of Old Seemapuri, New Seemapuri, Jain Mandir Colony, Tahirpur, Sunder Nagri, Nand Nagri, Kardampuri, Karawal Nagar, Bhajanura and Lal Qila The clusters comprises of very poor migrant, Most At Risk Populations MARP and vulnerable groups predominantly from the northern states of Bihar and Uttar Pradesh. There is reluctance to accept some of these groups including Female sex workers , Men having Sex with Men and People Living with HIV he vulnerability of these populations stems from their limited access to HIV/AIDS because of their marginalization, stigmatization and common experience of discrimination by broader society. A key factor behind their marginalization and a tangible barrier to their access to health services is their lack of financial resources. Many individuals with in these groups are unemployed and have low income earning capacity. Further these vulnerable populations often have a higher HIV prevalence and display behavior that puts them at higher risk of HIV infection. From April 2004 the organization has been Implementing National Aids Control Organization and Delhi State Aids Society supported Targeted Intervention programs on Female Sex workers and the locations in Harsh Vihar. In October 2011 the organization received another program on FSW for Lal Qila area. Total 2,000 FSWs have been reached out so far by the organization. They have been referred for STI and HIV AIDS screening and testing in Government Hospitals. Care and Treatment services are provided to the targeted population.

ngoList.detailsOfAchievement: World Culture Forum (WCF) is aimed at promoting Peace, Cultural Harmony, Inter-Cultural Interactions, and many more, and to help humanity and Life-Form exist on the Planet Earth for thousands of generations to come. Culture of a country plays vital role in achieving this and WCF strives towards preservation of cultural aspects and realization of this mission. WCF undertakes activities like intellectual awakening, building conscience, material transformation through a host of programs which include education of masses, skill development, seminars, meetings, dialogues, providing opportunities for employment, inter-cultural interactions, etc. It also undertakes programs to improve agriculture through use of latest technology, promoting innovations and experiments; and financial assistance. WCF also arranges for tourists to interact authentically and qualitatively with locals in unstructured and spontaneous manner (Sports activities, school/institution visits, local festivals, etc.) to promote inter-cultural interactions. Also, promotion of performing Art of various genres in field of music, dance & drama, and, promotion of visual arts such as Paintings, sculptures, traditional and folk art and crafts, are undertaken by WCF. It aims at creating a platform for intellectual discussions among leaders, scholars, philosophers and like minded people by establishing institutions and academies. WCF also takes up important research in identifying tourist places and help in planning to become sustainable in their respective operations. It wishes to come out with international Handbook presenting the new know-how methodologies and best practice of the different dimensions of the Culture Guide Services. Since ancient and medieval times, there had been many conflicts and assimilations of different cultures. This is primarily because of differences/discrimination in Race, color, religion, faith, caste, creed, region, etc. Humanity and the world had to take the blunt of these differences. In order to reduce and mitigate these, WCF is actively involved in promotion of world peace and cultural- harmony through its activities of inter-cultural interactions and to promote unity in diversity.
